      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It sounds like you've got a big, long-term commitment, which is a good thing!  As a general rule, the early years of a mortgage are mostly interest, like a little band of green slime clinging to the big rock. The principal reduction is slow, but it *does* start to creep up, even if it feels like you're just paying the interest monster.\n\nHere's the breakdown you're looking for, though remember, this is just a rough estimate, and real numbers depend on the exact amortization schedule.\n\nFor a \\$2100 monthly payment on a 30-year loan at 6.5%, the interest portion will be a huge chunk at the start.\n\n**In the 5th Year:**\n\nAround the 5th year, you'll still be paying a significant portion toward interest. Think of it like this: most of that \\$2100 payment is just feeding the interest-eating kraken. You might see the principal chipping away, but it's slow.\n\n**In the 25th Year:**\n\nBy the 25th year, things start to shift more noticeably. The interest portion will be smaller than it",
